r.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/28/02 8:27:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=32.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  EM Pulse</span><hr size=1> After reading that article on the main page about how an electromagnetic pulse from a nuke could wipe out electronics for miles around, I'm wondering how the electronics on the ship itself would fare.  Is it possible to shield electronics from an electromagnetic pulse?  Please say it's so!   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 201<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/29/02 9:33:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=32.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~macami/ez/spinthingie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: EM Pulse</span><hr size=1> Yes, sheilding is possible, though a guarded secret by the military on how much is needed.<br>
Every US military satellite is shielded against EMP effects.  Apparently, the object to be shielded<br>
needs only to be placed inside a metal container, with no openings, not even for a power cord<br>
or for ventilation.  That should do the trick. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 149<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/16/02 8:19:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=32.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: EM Pulse threat highly exagerated</span><hr size=1> Yet another way to protect the ship is to not use extremely huge blasts (above several megatonne) within the atmosphere. Orion is supposed to use less than 1kt, anywhere near the atmosphere, so it's not a problem.<br>
<br>
 If using smaller blasts, don't specifically design them to propduce EMP. Since Orion thrust bombs are not meant to produce EMP, but to provide thrust via vaporization of the propellant injected into the bomblets, EMP isn't a problem.<br>
<br>
Everything I've seen says that EMP is primarily a product of Gamma ray impacts with upper atmospheric particles. Please correct me if I'm wrong, but how are satellites threatened by sub-kilotonne -or even the bigger 20kt bombs of the big ground launched ship used in space?<br>
 Even if the ground launched ship were setting off the 20kt bombs within 200 miles of the surface, how is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> anything</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> threatened? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1934<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/26/02 4:54:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=32.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: EM Pulse threat highly exagerated</span><hr size=1> I believe it was 0.1Kt proposed for units. I hope nobody appears in a moment to drag this discussion down the oh so tired proliferation path...(please God no!). Going repeatedly off topic should be made a castratable offence.<br>
<br>
The range of EMP from such a small device has to be quite low but there is so much junk up there now it would be difficult to avoid frying something. If carefully planned it might be possible though. Orion is fast. No orbital trajectory. Straight up and out. Every object around the Earth is known and it's path determined. At the very least it should be possible to avoid the more important pieces of hardware. I might reread the EMP article on the website again to see if anything relevant exists there. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 583<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/26/02 7:22:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=32.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: EM Pulse threat highly exagerated</span><hr size=1> The fractional kiloton units are for the first a-bomb(s). This is to boost the ship with less mixture of surface material in the fallout. The stream of bombs rapidly rises thru the kiloton and dekakiloton range.<br>
<br>
